<F P=100> CENTRAL AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> El Salvador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Taiwan Prime Minister Attends Inauguration </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Taiwan Prime Minister Attends Inauguration </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0206082194 Taipei CNA in English 0658 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0206082194 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Huang Kwang-chun, Low Kwang-jen, and Danielle Yang] </F>
  [Text] San Salvador, June 1 (CNA) -- Republic of China 
[ROC] Premier Lien Chan attended the inauguration of Salvadoran 
President Armando Calderon Sol Wednesday [1 June] morning. 
  During the two-hour inauguration ceremony, Lien and his wife 
were seated as guests of honor next to other Central American 
leaders. 
  Calderon was named president of El Salvador under the 
witness 
of Salvadoran congressional leaders. After his inauguration, he 
delivered a 45-minute speech calling on his countrymen to help 
rebuild El Salvador, ravaged by 12 years of civil war. 
  After the ceremony, Lien met with Nicaraguan President 
Violeta Chamorro and Panamanian Vice President Guillermo Ford. 
  Meanwhile, during a television broadcast of the ceremony, a 
private El Salvador television station mistakenly aired a photo 
of the Communist Chinese flag alongside the photos of the ROC 
delegation. 
  The ROC Embassy in El Salvador immediately demanded an 
apology from the TV station. 
  Vice Foreign Affairs Minister Victor Manuel Lagos later 
apologized to ROC Ambassador Andrew Shen on behalf of El 
Salvador for the mistake. 
  Shen told CNA that the station also apologized for the 
mistake and agreed to make a correction during a news broadcast 
to be shown later in the evening. 
  Lien and his 21-member entourage will travel to Guatemala 
June 2 and is scheduled to return to Taipei June 7. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

