<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Finance Minister Lauds Restoration </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Finance Minister Lauds Restoration </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0206005694 Caracas Union Radio Network in Spanish 2200 GMT 
1 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0206005694 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Union Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Vicente Briceno from Miraflores Palace in </F>
Caracas; from the "Union Radio News" newscast] 
  [Text] As is known, the president of the Republic, in full 
use of his legislative powers, on 28 February decided to suspend 
economic guarantees nationwide. Today, however, following an end 
to the problems that prompted the suspension, President Caldera 
decided to reinstate these guarantees at a cabinet meeting. 
  According to Finance Minister Julio Sosa Rodriguez, once 
taxes on luxury goods and wholesale transactions were enacted, 
the continued suspension of economic guarantees was no longer 
justifiable. In turn, President Caldera decided to fulfill his 
promise to rescind the suspension soon after these two taxes 
were promulgated. 
  [Begin Sosa recording] The reinstatement of economic 
guarantees is not that significant in and of itself, because 
Venezuelans survived without such guarantees for 30 years. 
Nevertheless, this action is significant because it proves to 
various economic sectors that they can maintain confidence in 
the government's promises and its deeds. The government said it 
was going to do something, and it followed through on its 
promise. I believe this move has enormous significance. [end 
recording] 
  Sosa also expressed confidence that the dollar might fall 
below 150 bolivares. Sosa added that he hopes the psychological 
effects that triggered a rise in the price of the dollar will 
come to an end and, in turn, prompt the stabilization of the 
foreign exchange market. 
  Sosa said that as a result of his recent trip to the United 
States, delegations from the Inter-American Development Bank 
[IDB], World Bank, and IMF will soon visit Venezuela. He also 
indicated that IDB representatives will assist the government in 
planning a very important social housing program. The World Bank 
delegation will arrive in Venezuela on 13 June to consult with 
Venezuelan officials on the financial crisis. The IMF delegation 
will examine fiscal problems projected to occur within the 
1994-1996 period. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

