<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Minister Maintains Position </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Defense Minister Maintains Position </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0206020494 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Canal 
A Network in Spanish 0000 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0206020494 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Canal 
A Network </F>

<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Isabella Recio from the "Seven O'Clock Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] Christine Shelly, spokeswoman for the U.S. State 
Department's Bureau of International Narcotics Matters, has 
announced that a final decision is not expected before next week 
regarding U.S.-Colombian cooperation on information provided by 
U.S. radar installations in Leticia and Araracuara. Defense 
Minister Rafael Pardo and Air Force Commander Major General 
Alfonso Abondano commented on this topic today at a military 
ceremony. 
  During the ceremony to commemorate the 87th anniversary of 
the Cadets Military Academy, in addition to the traditional 
speeches and parades, there was time to discuss the U.S. radar 
dispute. Amid a downpour that resembled the storm now brewing 
in the country following the Pentagon's orders to suspend the 
operation of the two radar installations, Pardo discounted the 
U.S. position on whether or not unidentified planes should be 
shot down. 
  [Begin Pardo recording] The thing we oppose is that this 
decision was made unilaterally, despite the fact that this 
cooperation program has been in place for three years and that 
it has been a multilateral program. [end recording] 
  According to the defense minister, Colombia will continue to 
shoot down unidentified drug planes, and this policy will not 
change. 
  [Begin Pardo recording] Colombia has assumed this position 
following a thorough, 18-month legal review. We are very much 
convinced that our interpretation is correct, and we sincerely 
believe we have nothing to change in this regard. [end recording] 
  Meanwhile, the Colombian Air Force says the chances of a 
U.S. 
military plane being shot down are remote. 
  [Begin Abondano recording] We identify all planes visually 
before our pilots are authorized to shoot. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

