<F P=100> INTER-AMERICAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   SICA Officially Replaces ODECA </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SICA Officially Replaces ODECA </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0106195394 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 0131 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0106195394 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] San Salvador, 31 May (ACAN-EFE) -- The Central 
American Integration System (SICA) will legally replace the 
Organization of Central America States (ODECA) after the 
"Succession Act" is signed by the nations in the area, 
represented by their ambassadors, in San Salvador today. 
According to official reports, the Central American ambassadors 
have taken the last legal step to allow the transfer of ODECA 
assets, rights, and holdings to SICA. 
  ODECA was created on 12 December 1962, according to a 
presidential agreement called the "San Salvador Charter." SICA 
was established, according to the 13 December 1991 "Tegucigalpa 
Protocol," to coordinate regional integration actions and 
institutions determined by heads of state in the region. 
  A SICA communique explains that according to a resolution 
issued at the 13th Central American summit, held in Panama on 11 
December 1992, the institution had to begin operations, based in 
San Salvador, on 1 February 1993, and later settle its legal 
position, which it is doing today. "SICA asserts itself as a 
far-reaching, modern, humanist organization which has already 
yielded results by guaranteeing the coordination of the 
integration process in the fields of the economic, social, 
cultural, and political development of the isthmus," the 
communique states. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

