<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-107 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rum Production Projected Higher Than 1993 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rum Production Projected Higher Than 1993 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL0306013194 Havana Tele Rebelde and Cuba Vision Networks in 
Spanish 0000 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0306013194 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Tele Rebelde and Cuba Vision Networks </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Rum production projected for 1994 ensures a steady 
supply of ration quotas and the current levels of sales in the 
food stores. The Liquors and Beverages Union will produce 33 
million liters of rum in 1994, a volume slightly higher than in 
1993. This was announced by union director Jose Manuel de la 
Osa. The Sugar Industry Ministry and people's government 
productions will allow the supply to reach 41 million liters in 
1994. This does not mean, however, that rum sales can be 
deregulated, like what happened with cigarettes. The industry 
has the capacity to increase its volume of production, but does 
not have enough molasses and alcohols to satisfy the rum demand 
in the retail chain. De la Osa pointed out that increases in 
those essential raw materials will make it possible to increase 
rum production in the future. For the present, ration quotas per 
family unit, as well as the levels of distribution to the retail 
food chain, will continue in Havana and the rest of Cuba. 

</TEXT>

