<H3> <TI>   Safety Secretary Remarks on Dismissal of Police </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Safety Secretary Remarks on Dismissal of Police </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0206224594 Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1300 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0206224594 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1300 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=105> Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Rebeca Sanchez from the "Early Morning" newscast] </F>
  [Text] In the past 17 months, 2,040 metropolitan policemen 
have been dismissed on charges of insolence, abuse of authority, 
physical aggression, intimidation, blackmail, and for soliciting 
bribes, reported General Rene Monterrubio, roads and safety 
secretary, when he appeared before the Federal District's 
Assembly of Representatives. 
  [Begin Monterrubio recording] As a result of procedures for 
police justice during the past 17 months, police authorities 
approved 2,040 discharge or dismissal resolutions; 212 
admonishment resolutions; 212 [word indistinct] charges; 1,209 
arrests; and 105 admonishments [as heard]. [end recording] 
  Commenting on his organization's achievements, Monterrubio 
cited this past April's creation of the Honor and Justice 
Council to fight impunity and improve discipline of the police 
corps. He said there have been 18,312 preventable crimes in the 
Federal District so far this year. 
  He said his work as head of the Metropolitan Police is aimed 
at changing its image, performing a professional job, and 
consolidating an administrative structure capable of offering a 
better service to the community. 
  [Begin Monterrubio recording] The police must represent a 
guarantee for the people's security and peace, not be the cause 
of insecurity and unrest. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

