<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Electoral Developments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Electoral Developments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0306002394 </F>
<F P=103> PA0306002394 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on developments related to the elections scheduled for 
21 August. 
  While visiting two towns in Chiapas State, Rafael Aguilar 
Talamantes, presidential candidate for the Cardenist Front for 
National Reconstruction Party, cited his party's support for 
farm occupations and takeovers. He said "we must discuss each 
case and hold talks to correct any abuses, even those committed 
on our side." (Mexico City XEW Television Network in Spanish 
0430 GMT 27 May 94) 
  During his second day in Chiapas State, candidate Aguilar 
Talamantes told the residents of Guitiapan the "method of 
struggle Subcommander Marcos and the Zapatists use cannot work 
or effect good results; we know that." (Mexico City XEW 
Television Network in Spanish 0430 GMT 28 May 94) 
  PRD candidate Cardenas has visited Mesa de Alcoyotic, Mexico 
State, and commented on the announcement the PRD (Party of the 
Democratic Revolution) and PAN (National Action Party) had 
established a pact of nonaggression: "We do not sign pacts. We 
will behave respectably and adhere to PRD principles and respond 
how we must." He also expressed support for the idea of more 
debates with the other presidential candidates. (Mexico City XEW 
Television Network in Spanish 0430 GMT 27 May 94) 
  Commenting on an invitation from PRI (Institutional 
Revolutionary Party) candidate Zedillo to the other presidential 
candidates to hold a debate, PRD candidate Cardenas has asked 
the other candidates to agree on "this next debate, as well as 
on the others we may hold up to 21 August." He also proposed 
holding debates between two candidates. Cardenas has also said 
the news media, Televisa, Television Azteca, and Multivision in 
particular, should give all the candidates the opportunity to 
comment on the debates after they are over. (Mexico City XEW 
Television Network in Spanish 0430 GMT 28 May 94) 
  In Guerrero State, PAN candidate Fernandez has said he 
disagreed with Zedillo's proposal to hold a debate with all the 
presidential candidates. He did not rule out the idea, however, 
saying he supported "finding mechanisms and reasonable formulas 
to continue the debates." The debates, he said, should not be an 
"ambush to stop PAN's struggle in winning the Presidency." The 
PAN candidate also endorsed a final revision of the electoral 
lists with the participation of all the political parties. 
(Mexico City XEW Television Network in Spanish 0430 GMT 27 May 
94) 
  At the conclusion of a meeting with businessmen from the 
southern area of the Federal District, candidate Fernandez 
announced his party and the PRD have established a "pact of 
nonaggression" in order to end mutual accusations. During his 
meeting with the businessmen, he pledged to amend the Federal 
Labor Law, without "hurting the gains of the workers," and to 
implement a "social market economy based on freedom and private 
initiative." (Mexico City EL FINANCIERO in Spanish 26 May 94 p12) 
  Talking to tourism students at the San Angel Higher Studies 
Center, Mexican Green Ecologist Party presidential candidate 
Jorge Gonzalez described as "totally undemocratic" candidate 
Fernandez' rejection of a debate with all the presidential 
candidates. (Mexico City XEW Television Network in Spanish 0430 
GMT 28 May 94) 
  At the Isthmus of Tehuantepec, Marcela Lombardo, 
presidential 
candidate of the Popular Socialist Party, has told reporters she 
accepts Zedillo's invitation to participate in a debate. 
(Mexico City XEW Television Network in Spanish 0430 GMT 28 May 
94) 
  Pablo Emilio Madero, presidential candidate of the National 
Opposition Union (UNO), began a visit to Guanajuato State that 
will take him to 14 municipalities. He met with his supporters 
at Dolores Hidalgo Square where he said "peace and tranquility 
should not be the lack of armed violence only; there should be 
peace and tranquility because the votes are respected." (Mexico 
City XEW Television Network in Spanish 0430 GMT 27 May 94) 
  If elected, "I will make the tax burden more equitable," 
candidate Madero told his supporters at Juventino Rosas during 
his second day of campaigning in Guanajuato. (Mexico City XEW 
Television Network in Spanish 0430 GMT 28 May 94) 
  Speaking to party supporters, PRI national leader Ignacio 
Pichardo Pagaza has said the PRI trusts it will win in at least 
40 districts of Mexico City. He said the Mexican revolution 
will be maintained until the turn of the century with "the 
majority vote of the Mexican people." He spoke after swearing in 
Fernando Lerdo de Tejada and Juan Carlos Sanchez Magallan as PRI 
president and secretary general, respectively, of the Federal 
District. (Mexico City UNOMASUNO in Spanish 1 Jun 94 p 9) 
  During her first day of campaigning in Chiapas State, Labor 
Party (PT) presidential candidate Cecilia Soto Gonzalez agreed 
to hold a debate with the other eight presidential candidates 
and proposed it be held on 1 June. (Mexico City XEW Television 
Network in Spanish 0430 GMT 27 May 94) 
  While in San Cristobal de las Casas, Chiapas State, Soto 
said 
the peace process is not advancing, because "the state and 
federal governments lack a sufficient commitment to resolve the 
problem of landownership and land reform." (Mexico City XEW 
Television Network in Spanish 0430 GMT 28 May 94) 
  In Mexico State, Jorge Gonzalez Torres, Mexican Green 
Ecologist Party presidential candidate, has said Article 27 of 
the Constitution had to be amended back to the way it was 
originally drafted in order for the 21 August elections to be 
credible and honest. (Mexico City XEW Television Network in 
Spanish 0430 GMT 27 May 94) 
  Today, Alvaro Perez Trevino, presidential candidate of the 
Authentic Party of the Mexican Revolution, said Ernesto Zedillo 
is the country's best option. He reiterated what he said a 
month ago in the studios of Radio Acir. Trevino said if he does 
not win the elections, he will support Zedillo. He has said his 
party is not a parastate party or a satellite of the PRI. 
(Mexico City Radio Acir Network in Spanish 0000 GMT 1 Jun 94) 
  During a ceremony at PRI headquarters, candidate Zedillo 
spoke in favor of maintaining a "healthy distance" between the 
government and PRI. Zedillo has said: "We want a nation of 
welfare, opportunities, and a firm hope," saying poverty in 
Mexico does not admit "indifference or evasion." Zedillo has 
said his efforts will be directed at increasing the people's 
security and property, eliminating impunity, and fighting 
narcotrafficking. Zedillo has recognized the merits of 
President Carlos, saying he has left the PRI government a legacy 
of patriotism and undaunted determination. (Mexico City EL 
FINANCIERO in Spanish 30 May 94 p 6) 
  As instructed by Zedillo, the PRI has sent representatives 
to 
Japan, the United States, South America, Spain, and Portugal to 
brief the country representatives on the electoral process that 
will take place in Mexico in August, Jose Angel Gurria has 
announced. They will strive to guarantee the elections in Mexico 
will be clean so that foreign investors will not lose confidence 
in Mexico. (Monterrey EL NORTE (Foreign Edition) in Spanish 30 
May 94 p 4A) 
  During a meeting with reporters in Saltillo, Cahuila State, 
Zedillo has said that so far none of the presidential candidates 
has formally replied to his proposal to hold a debate. He said 
he hoped all the candidates would agree to participate. He 
described the disappointment among PRI members regarding the 
selection of candidates as normal, adding the PRI "has again 
shown its strength, unity, and will continue to strive to win 
democratically." (Mexico City XEW Television Network in Spanish 
0430 GMT 27 May 94) 
  Zedillo has flown to Ciudad Juarez, Chihuahua State, and 
visited an assembly plant. He has promised to sustain sources 
of employment but, rather, "under decent conditions" for 
workers. During a meeting with local businessmen, he heard of 
their views on the bad economic situation, the crime wave, and 
drug trafficking. "We are going to reform our country's 
apparatus of justice," he said. Zedillo also met privately with 
PAN Governor Francisco Barrio. If elected, the PRI candidate 
affirmed, he will maintain close cooperation with local 
governments ruled by opposition parties. (Mexico City XEW 
Television Network in Spanish 0430 GMT 27 May 94) 
  Zedillo has expressed reservations about signing several 
points of the Agreement for Democracy. He asked for a four-week 
period to present suggestions to the commission sponsoring the 
agreement. Zedillo has said the idea behind the agreement is 
good but that the agenda must be broader on judicial matters and 
on the division of power. So far, only PAN candidate Diego 
Fernandez, PRD candidate Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, and PT candidate 
Cecilia Soto have signed the agreement. (Monterrey EL NORTE 
(Foreign Edition) in Spanish 31 May 94 p 1A) 

</TEXT>

