<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lewis Galindo Views U.S. Military Installations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Lewis Galindo Views U.S. Military Installations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0206165594 Panama City EL PANAMA AMERICA in Spanish 30 May 
94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> PA0206165594 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City EL PANAMA AMERICA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Gabriel Lewis Galindo, designated foreign minister 
by president-elect Ernesto Perez Balladares, has said that 
Panama will study with "receptiveness" a formal U.S. proposal in 
terms of maintaining certain military installations on the 
Isthmus. 
  Lewis Galindo's declarations were made after his meeting 
with 
Senator Christopher Dodd, chairman of the Senate Foreign 
Relations Committee. During his first visit to Washington since 
he was designated, Lewis Galindo spoke extensively with several 
Democrat and Republican congressmen. 
  Recent publications indicate official planners are 
considering the possibility of maintaining U.S. air and 
communications installations in Panama. When questioned on this 
issue, however, the foreign minister highlighted that the 
current priority is to assure the transfer of the Canal to 
Panamanian control without setbacks and with the greatest 
efficiency possible. 
  Meanwhile, at the meeting held with James Fall III, U.S. 
Treasury deputy assistant secretary (Developing Nations), Lewis 
Galindo assured Fall that U.S. dollars "will continue to be the 
main currency used in Panama." 
  Today, Monday, the designated foreign minister will meet at 
the White House with Anthony Lake, assistant to the President 
for National Security Affairs, and tomorrow he will meet with 
Secretary of State Warren Christopher. Tomorrow Galindo also 
will meet with Enrique Iglesias, president of the Inter-American 
Development Bank. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

