<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chubut Governor Concerned Over Production Rate </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chubut Governor Concerned Over Production Rate </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0206201194 Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS in Spanish 
1941 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY0206201194 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Buenos Aires, 1 Jun (NA) -- Chubut Governor Carlos 
Maestro said today that people in his province are concerned 
"over the lack of incentives for the development of productive 
activities, specially for small and medium-sized industries." 
  Maestro emphasized: "The lack of encouragement for regional 
economies has caused many companies to collapse." 
  He went to Government House to meet Presidential Secretary 
General Eduardo Bauza and Interior Minister Carlos Ruckauf. He 
said: "Chubut is trying to implement key mechanisms to 
revitalize production." 
  Maestro noted: "This involves fiscal policies like the 
removal of taxes. We have removed energy taxes and rural real 
estate taxes and are now implementing a dynamic loan policy." 
  The Chubut governor emphasized that his province "currently 
has a $100-million loan portfolio for productive sectors, with 
very low interest rates, 10-year repayment periods, and up to 
three-year grace periods to begin repaying loans." 
  The Radical Civic Union governor concluded: "By implementing 
all these measures, we are trying to alleviate a very complex 
situation in the field of production." 

</TEXT>

