<H3> <TI>   Israel's Peres Meets Menem, Holds News Conference </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Israel's Peres Meets Menem, Holds News Conference </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0206140094 Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS in Spanish 
0041 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY0206140094 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Buenos Aires, 1 Jun (NA) -- Israeli Foreign Minister 
Shim'on Peres said tonight that the "hand of a foreign country" 
was involved in the attack against his country's embassy in 
Buenos Aires on 17 March 1992. Peres made clear, however, that 
"the details will be known only when the investigation has been 
completed." 
  Peres condemned the presence of Nazis in Argentina, saying 
"assassins must be punished wherever they might be because the 
law does not give anyone a license to kill another human being." 
Peres said he is "against all assassins in history." 
  The Israeli foreign minister held a news conference at 
Government House after his one-hour meeting with President 
Carlos Menem. Peres briefed Menem on the status of the Middle 
East peace process since the historic signing of an agreement 
with the Palestinian people. 
  Peres said he started a round of briefings with U.S. 
President Bill Clinton "and wanted to end it with President 
Menem." 
  His meeting with the president was possible because the 
plane 
carrying the foreign minister from Santiago to Madrid made a 
technical stopover at Ezeiza Airport, which gave Peres a chance 
to request an audience with President Menem. 
  Peres said the peace process with Yasir 'Arafat's 
Palestinians "was achieved and is irreversible." He also said 
that his intention was "to move forward and not backward." 
  Peres recognized that the signing of the agreement's first 
chapter with the Palestinians "was not an easy matter. We had 
problems, but I think it is a great achievement." 
  Peres said Israel "is negotiating with Syrians, Jordanians, 
Lebanese, and also with Palestinians on the issue of autonomy" 
because we want "to create a new way (of life) in the Middle 
East where security for the four nations will be guaranteed, 
permitting the development of an economic system that will allow 
these nations to improve their future prospects within the 
boundaries of respect for human rights and freedom." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

