<F P=100> Chile </F>
<H3> <TI>   Authorities Concerned Over Economy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Authorities Concerned Over Economy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0306013394 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1707 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY0306013394 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Santiago, 2 Jun (EFE) -- Several Chilean 
authorities and business sector leaders agreed today that 
persistently high inflation rates, increased unemployment rates, 
and a drop in investments are causing concern within the Chilean 
Government and the private sector. 
  Data disclosed on 1 June by the National Statistics 
Institute 
(INE) shows that the annual inflation rate remains at 12.7 
percent, following a rise of 1.4 percent in May, while 
unemployment rose to 5.3 percent; a 0.9 percent increase over 
the past 12 months. 
  All this, in addition to a growth of only 3.4 percent of the 
GDP during the first quarter and a persistent drop in the 
exchange rate, makes businessmen fear that the economic 
adjustment the government has been implementing for the past 
year may became negative and that the Chilean economy may slow 
down. 
  Chilean Economy Under Secretary Carlos Mladinic asserted 
that 
these figures reveal that the struggle to curb inflation--one of 
the government's main objectives and the main reason for the 
adjustment--is not easy and demands great discipline and 
austerity in public and private expenditures. 
  Mladinic denied that the Chilean economy has been 
drastically 
over-adjusted, adding that it is only "logical" that the 
measures to reduce expenditures would increase the unemployment 
rate. 
  Mladinic added that the government is maintaining its goal 
of 
an inflation rate not higher than 11 percent for this year. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-33224 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat107_n_94005" </HT>


