<F P=100> Chile </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Reports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0206235494 </F>
<F P=103> PY0206235494 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities in Chile monitored through 2 June. 
  A public sector and private business commission will visit 
the PRC between 25 and 31 May and then go to Hong Kong to 
promote commercial relations. The negotiations will be conducted 
by Chilean exporters. The delegation will be headed by Economy 
Minister Alvaro Garcia and by Exporters Association President 
Ronald Bown. Chilean exports to PRC last year totalled $183.5 
million, while imports totaled $212.5 million. (Santiago LA 
TERCERA DE LA HORA in Spanish 21 May 94 p 5) 
  The Chilean Exporters Association reported that 122,063,885 
boxes of fruits were exported during the 1993-1994 season, up by 
3.5 percent compared with the previous season. The United States 
is the leading importer with $49.8 million worth of fruit, while 
Europe imported $46.8 million worth. (Santiago EL MERCURIO in 
Spanish 21 May 94 pp 1, 23) 
  The Chilean and Venezuelan trade balance has been 
unfavorable 
for Chile since the economic complementation accord was enforced 
in April 1993. The Central Bank of Chile reported that exports 
to that country dropped by 6.2 percent between July and December 
1993, and by 5.8 percent during the first quarter of this year, 
when sales totalled $14.5 million. The trade balance registered 
a $68-million deficit in 1993 following the purchase of oil and 
heating oil. (Madrid EFE in Spanish 1458 GMT 25 May 94) 
  The Central Bank of Chile on 22 May reported that Chilean 
foreign investments rose $188.8 million in the first four months 
of the year. The biggest investments were made in Panama--$215.5 
million; Argentina--$61 million; and Peru--$33.7 million. The 
cumulated foreign investment was $1,233 billion from 1975 to 
April 1994 (Santiago EL MERCURIO in Spanish 23 May 94 pp B1-B2) 
  Preliminary figures released by the Central Bank of Chile 
show the GDP increased 3.4 percent during the first quarter of 
the year. Fishing registered the highest increase with 21.3 
percent; transport and communications, 8.1 percent; industry, 
5.5 percent; electricity, gas, and water, 5 percent; financial 
services, 4.3 percent; and personal services, including 
education and public and private health, 3.4 percent. Mining 
activities dropped by 0.7 percent and forestry activities 
dropped by 0.5 percent. (Santiago EL MERCURIO in Spanish 24 May 
94 pp A1-A12) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

