<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-107 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  30 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Meets Israel's Shimon Peres </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister Meets Israel's Shimon Peres </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0206222894 Santa Fe de Bogota EL TIEMPO in Spanish 30 May 
94 pp 1A, 19A </F>

<F P=103> PA0206222894 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota EL TIEMPO </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Democracy was not the only protagonist on 29 May. 
Peace was too, and it arrived on board a plane hoping for a 
better future, and this was the message Israeli Foreign Minister 
Shimon Peres brought with him. 
  Foreign Minister Noemi Sanin, accompanied by a large 
delegation of the Jewish and Palestinian communities residing in 
the Colombian capital, received Peres at Catam Military Airport 
in western Santa Fe de Bogota. 
  Peres, on a brief tour of Latin America that includes only 
Mexico, Colombia, and Chile, will discuss topics such as 
economic rapprochement and technological cooperation with 
Colombian officials. The topic of peace predominated, however, 
during the foreign minister's news conference at the Catam 
runway. 
  The Colombian foreign minister said: "Peres is a protagonist 
of peace. Colombia must pay homage to him for his efforts and 
the success he has had in both this first chapter of peace 
between Israel and the Palestinians and for everything he is 
doing in the Middle East, as an example to the world on how 
peace should be made." 
  Peres stressed the importance of the democratic process he 
witnessed upon his arrival. "Colombia, despite the bad press, 
has always been a country that is stronger due to its votes 
rather than its bullets. I am certain the results of today's 
elections will allow it to continue down the path of economic 
recovery and growth in other sectors." 
  "Just as you are doing, we are trying to consolidate peace 
among our people and in our region. In Israeli, we are 
determined to continue with the upcoming chapters of peace in 
the process we have begun," Peres said. 
  With contagious optimism, the Israeli foreign minister 
expressed his conviction the peace being built in the Middle 
East will be a solid and lasting one. "I believe the entire 
world is progressing from a history of wars to the creation of 
peace. Nothing that is important in life can be achieved 
through war. What can be achieved through war has ceased to be 
important," he added. 
  According to the foreign minister, the step that was taken 
with the implementation of the Palestinian autonomies in the 
Gaza Strip and the Cisjordanian city of Jericho, as established 
in the declaration signed by the Palestine Liberation 
Organization (PLO) and Israel in Washington last September, is 
irreversible. "I believe we are deeply interested in securing 
peace for our children. We are tired of war. Neither side has 
achieved anything by military means," he said. The peace 
process in the Middle East is loaded with obstacles, however. 
Perez' view is pragmatic. 
  Asked about the statement by PLO President Yasir 'Arafat 
about the recent call for a "holy war" for the liberation of 
Jerusalem, Peres said actions are far more important than words, 
adding "we are satisfied that despite Arafat's statements he has 
continued to fulfill our agreement." 
  Peres emphatically said: "Jerusalem will remain a united 
city, the capital of Israel. Jerusalem is politically closed 
but religiously open. We are not going to turn it into a 
Berlin, divided in two. It will be open to all religions." 
  Peres anticipated a new era in relations with Catholics and 
Muslims. "We will sign an agreement with the Vatican in 
Jerusalem and exchange ambassadors this year. This was not an 
ordinary political move. It is something that took 1,994 years 
to happen. All of the sacred sites will remain open to all 
religions," he reiterated. 
  For Peres, the key element of the changes that are occurring 
worldwide is the economy. "If one has an adequate economy, one 
obtains adequate results," he said. He affirmed, therefore, 
there will be no peace in Israel if this country remains an 
island of prosperity in a sea of poverty. "We will do 
everything within our means to improve standards of living in 
all parts of the region, not only in Israel." 
  Peres mentioned an economic example of the importance of 
peace in the region. According to him, the Middle East spent 
more than $1 trillion in 10 years to buy bombs. If half this 
amount had been spent on education, the Middle East would be a 
very prosperous region, he said. 
  Peres offered his country's technological assistance to 
Colombia. "We will gladly share whatever experience we have in 
the agricultural field. Israel has improved its agricultural 
production by 1,200 percent in 25 years without water or land." 
  He said Latin America is also experiencing a profound 
transformation, a factor which plays a significant role on the 
world stage. "Colombia, one of the four most important 
countries in Latin America, will play its proper role," he said. 
  Nevertheless, Peres reserved his highest praise for the 
Colombian foreign minister. "We are very happy to improve 
relations between Colombia and Israel. The Colombian foreign 
minister's visit to Israel was very successful. She made a 
magnificent impression on us." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-33235 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat107_o_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-107 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  31 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Article Views Suspended U.S. Radar Operations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Article Views Suspended U.S. Radar Operations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0206185794 Santa Fe de Bogota EL TIEMPO in Spanish 31 May 
94 pp 1A, 11A </F>

<F P=103> PA0206185794 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota EL TIEMPO </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Since the Cartagena Agreement on the struggle 
against drug trafficking was signed on 15 February 1990, which 
includes the United States, Colombia, Peru, and Bolivia, never 
has such a tense situation been generated among the signatory 
nations as the one observed last weekend between the United 
States, Colombia, and Peru. 
  One month ago, the Pentagon issued an order to suspend 
operations of the two radars that detect aircraft. These radars 
operate in Colombia as a result of that agreement. The same 
decision was made regarding the radars that operate in Peru. 
  This decision -- labeled by high-ranking Colombian 
Government 
spokespersons as "not consulted, untimely, unilateral, and 
discourteous" -- has not been officially communicated to the 
authorities by the U.S. Government which has preferred to remain 
silent. 
  The incident began on Sunday, 1 May. On that day, the 
Colombian Air Force officer in charge of radar operations in 
Aracuara and Leticia (Amazonas), officially communicated to the 
Defense Ministry that the passing on of information on flights 
from the radars was being suspended by the U.S. military without 
any explication. Since then and to the present, the two 
Colombian radars have not been operating. 
  The order was issued by the Pentagon to the soldiers through 
the U.S. Southern Command in Panama. A high-ranking government 
official said: "The news was baffling although at the beginning 
it was said that the suspension was only for eight days." 
  The following day, a Colombian Government official contacted 
the embassy, which had no official information. At that point, 
President Gaviria decided to request a formal explanation for 
what was happening. That was 28 days ago, and no reply has been 
received as yet. 
  In Colombia, the matter was handled with confidentiality, 
until Sunday, when U.S. daily THE WASHINGTON POST reported that 
Colombia and Peru "would take reprisals" against the United 
States as a result of its decision to suspend operations of the 
four radars. Those "reprisals" would be the decision to ship out 
of the country two 30-year-old radars that were used in the 
Vietnam War and which have been of no use in the struggle 
against drug trafficking for the past month. A government 
spokesman said that of course the removal of the radars would 
also be accompanied by "a cordial invitation" to the U.S. 
soldiers and experts in charge of their maintenance to leave the 
country. No government official has confirmed or denied that 
decision. A government spokesman consulted by EL TIEMPO, 
however, said "it is obvious that if the radars are useless, 
there is no sense in keeping them or their technicians in 
Colombian territory." 
  Meanwhile, the authorities know that drug traffickers' 
illegal flights have been on the rise in the past month due to 
the total absence of control in that Amazon area. This is where 
drugs from Bolivia and Peru enter Colombia. 
  The official report on the illegal flights indicate that in 
1993, in that area, 375 aircraft were detected and up until 1 
May this year, 200 flights were reported. This past month an 
average of one illegal flight per day has been added. 
  The government's final determination on the U.S. decision 
will only be adopted when the United States gives a formal 
explanation of what is occurring. In the meantime, it is only 
known that the suspension of radars operations was decided by 
the Pentagon, apparently without the blessing of the State 
Department or the Justice Department. What some government 
officials fear is that an explanation will never be received, 
therefore Colombia will have to make a decision. 
  Those who are caught driving under the influence of drugs 
or other substances will be sentenced to pay the minimum of 20 
equivalent salaries, and their driver licenses will be suspended 
for up to a year. They will even be arrested for 24 hours, and 
their vehicles will be impounded. 
  Likewise, those who, through a medical examination, are 
found 
addicted to any psychotropic substance will not get their 
licenses renewed, and those who, after obtaining their licenses, 
become addicts or second time offenders in illegal possession of 
ammunition, arms, or explosives will get their licenses revoked. 
  Heads of public offices are authorized to unilaterally 
breach 
work contracts when public employees go to their workplaces 
under the influence of any substance or when they consume or 
incite others to consume drugs in the workplace. 
  Furthermore, all public employees of sound mind are 
forbidden 
from using and consuming drugs and psychotropic substances. 
They will be penalized as stipulated by Decree-Law 2400 of 1968 
and by other regulations that supervise public posts. 
  The consumption of psychotropic substances and drugs is also 
forbidden to those who, due to the nature of their jobs or 
professions, impose risks to others. 
  The Decree includes in this category drivers of any type of 
vehicle, pilots, ship captains, aviation students, flight 
instructors, machinists and operators, doctors, dentists, and 
other health professionals who deal with or tend combustible or 
flammable materials and substances, including explosives, toxic, 
poisonous, corrosive, or radioactive substances, as well as 
those who bear or ship arms, air traffic controllers and 
operators, and all ground plane maintenance and support 
technicians. 
  The violation of these regulations by these professionals 
will lead to the suspension, disqualification, or revocation of 
the license or permit to practice their professions. 
  The family, community, society, and state will be 
responsible 
for promoting or implementing policies geared toward avoiding 
and undermining the causes and consequences of drug consumption. 
  This is why the National Drug Council will have to evaluate 
the scope of the problem and coordinate with other governmental 
institutions projects of prevention and programs that will be 
implemented locally, regionally, and nationally. 
  The country's radio and television stations will also have 
to 
air campaigns aimed at fighting drug trafficking and consumption 
as often and as long as the National Drug Council deems 
convenient. 
  To that effect, the government ordered the council to issue, 
within 30 days, pertinent regulations and asked the 
Communications Ministry to continue to promote and develop 
communication strategies to overcome this problem; besides, the 
Health Ministry, secretariats, and departmental services will 
embark on rehabilitation campaigns and programs at the level of 
their treatment facilities. 
  Finally, public and private employers must conduct permanent 
prevention campaigns to make preventive measures effective, and 
they must let authorities inspect and investigate as needed. 
  Drug use and consumption were banned from public places, 
including theaters and stadiums, as well as ships, planes, 
government offices, restaurants, bars, night clubs, hotels, and 
parks. Managers and directors of public places will be able to 
expel drug consumers. Those public places that allow drug 
consumption will be temporarily closed for up to 30 days. 
  Drugs whose effects enhance athletic performance, reduce 
anxiety, and artificially diminish exhaustion cannot be used in 
any sport activities. Doctors who prescribe these type of 
substances to athletes will no longer be able to practice in the 
country. 
  Those who drive under the influence of drugs will be 
sentenced to pay up to 20 minimum monthly salaries, and their 
driver licenses will be suspended for up to a year. They will 
also be detained for 24 hours. 
  No public or private employee will be able to go to his 
workplace under the influence of drugs or to consume them while 
working. Violating this regulation will cause employers to 
breach his contract. 
  The decree also stipulates prison inmates are forbidden from 
possessing or consuming drugs and psychotropic substances, as 
stipulated by 1993 Law No. 65 of the Penitentiary Code. 
  After medical, psychological, and psychiatric evaluations 
are 
made, prison medical services will include rehabilitation 
treatment for inmates who are consuming psychotropic substances 
to help them recover. This regulation does not exempt them, 
however, from being penalized, as stipulated by the law. 
  Penitentiary and surveillance guard members who are caught 
consuming or possessing drugs or who bring drugs to prisons will 
be fired. Disciplinary measures will be taken as well. 
  From now on, those who request gun licenses will be given a 
psychological and physical aptitude test. In case they are 
found to be drug or psychotropic substance addicts, their 
licenses will be revoked. Furthermore, those who bear arms, 
explosives, or ammunition under the influence of these 
substances will be sentenced to pay up to the minimum of one 
monthly salary, although this does not mean they are exempt from 
disciplinary measures. Second time offenders will have their 
gun licenses permanently revoked as stipulated by Decree 2535 of 
1993. 
  The Minors Protection Code stipulates minors, pregnant or 
nursing women, and those who are considered unstable according 
to the Civil Code are forbidden to consume drugs. The 
regulation indicates women in either one of these two conditions 
or minors who consume drugs will be sent to a family counselor 
who will be able to reprimand the dependent minors' parents, to 
grant custody to a close relative, to place them in a foster 
home or a special protection center, or even to begin procedures 
to adopt neglected minors. 
  These measures are aimed at guaranteeing personal care and 
abating the perils that may threaten minors' health and morale. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-33236 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat107_p_94001" </HT>


