<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   State Effects of PSDB-PFL Alliance Examined </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    State Effects of PSDB-PFL Alliance Examined </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0306014594 Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL in Portuguese 31 May 
94 p 7 </F>

<F P=103> PY0306014594 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Marcio Aith] </F>
  [Text] The PFL [Liberal Front Party] has not helped the 
PSDB [Brazilan Social Democracy Party]-- at least not in the 
states where the coalition between the two parties was made 
formal in the electoral colleges in which presidential candidate 
Fernando Henrique Cardoso and the PSDB were already strong. 
  According to polls, gubernatorial candidates Mario Covas and 
Marcelo Alencar are the favorites in Sao Paulo and Rio de 
Janeiro, respectively. Both, who belong to the PSDB, have 
received weak PFL support. 
  Although the PSDB coalition with the PFL has increased the 
former's electoral chances in Pernambuco, Miguel Arraes -- the 
PSB [Brazilian Socialist Party] gubernatorial candidate -- is 
the main favorite. Arraes supports Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva's 
presidential candidacy. In Parana, the PFL-PSDB coalition's 
strongest candidate is Jaime Lerner, of the PDT [Democratic 
Labor Party]. 
  In Bahia, Santa Catarina, Ceara, Minas Gerais, and Para, the 
coalition was not made concrete because of lack of interest on 
the part of the two parties' regional leaders. In these states 
the PFL is strong, and will be an important PSDB rival. 
  Presidential candidate Cardoso told reporter Ana Carolina 
Silveira in Campinas (Sao Paulo) yesterday: "The parties are 
establishing coalition in different ways. We thought that 
Brazil was uniform, but it is not. There can be no vertical 
coalition, and the parties are adopting different coalitions in 
the different states." 
  The latest coalitions -- the PT has decided to support 
gubernatorial candidate Jutahy Magalhaes in Bahia, and the PMDB 
[Brazilian Democratic Movement Party] gave up the idea of 
presenting a candidate in Parana -- were decided upon over the 
last weekend and on 30 May. They are as follow: 
