<F P=100> Uruguay </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Reports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0306031194 </F>
<F P=103> PY0306031194 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities monitored through 2 June. 
  Unemployment in Montevideo Department stood at 8.7 percent 
in 
the period extending from February to April 1994, thus 
registering a slight increase compared with the first quarter of 
the year, in which the unemployment rate was 8.1 percent. 
(Montevideo EL PAIS in Spanish 27 May 94 Market Indicators 
Section p 1) 
  The Central Bank reported on 26 May that the central 
government registered a $22.6 million surplus in the first two 
months of the year, thus reversing last month's negative result. 
(Montevideo EL OBSERVADOR ECONOMICO in Spanish 27 May 94 p 11) 
  According to figures disclosed by the Central Bank on 26 
May, 
the trade deficit continued to grow in March, totaling $741.2 
million over the last 12 months, which represents 5.6 percent of 
GDP. In the first quarter of the year, the trade deficit was 55 
percent higher than the corresponding period last year, 
amounting to $175 million. (Montevideo EL OBSERVADOR ECONOMICO 
in Spanish 27 May 94 p 10) 
  According to information disclosed by the National 
Statistics 
Institute on 27 May, salaries declined in real terms in April, 
both in the private and public sectors, by 0.9 and 2.8 percent 
respectively. Despite this decline, salaries in the Civil 
Service increased by 1.2 percent in real terms in the first four 
months of the year. Salaries in the private sector, however, 
declined by 0.3 percent in the said period both in Montevideo 
and in the interior. (Montevideo EL OBSERVADOR ECONOMICO in 
Spanish 30 May 94 p 9) 
  Wholesale prices went up 2.6 percent in May, thus totaling 
11 
percent so far this year and 30.9 percent over the last 12 
months. This information was released by the Central Bank on 30 
May. The items that registered the highest increase were oil 
by-products (7.2 percent), nonmetal minerals (4.8 percent), and 
clothing (4.5 percent). (Montevideo EL OBSERVADOR ECONOMICO in 
Spanish 31 May 94 p 8) 
  Uruguay's trade with its partners from the Common Market of 
the South, Mercosur, grew by 19 percent in the first quarter of 
the year compared with the corresponding period last year, thus 
representing 47 percent of Uruguay's overall trade. Uruguay's 
leading trading partner is Brazil, whose exports to our country 
amounted to $157.7 million in the first quarter, thus 
registering a 29 percent growth compared with 1993. Uruguay's 
trade deficit with its Mercosur partners added up to $122.4 
million in the said period. (Montevideo EL OBSERVADOR ECONOMICO 
in Spanish 31 May 94 p 8) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

