<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   SELA Position on `Hostile' U.S. Policy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SELA Position on `Hostile' U.S. Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL0406130794 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 2300 
GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0406130794 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Exclusive" program] </F>
  [Text] The Latin American Economic System [SELA] on 3 June 
condemned the U.S. blockade of Cuba during the closing of its 
20th ministerial council in Mexico City. A resolution to 
promote the integration of Cuba, Suriname, and the Dominican 
Republic into the association of Caribbean states, scheduled to 
meet in Barbados in July, was also made. The 27 nations that 
make up SELA stated unanimously that free trade contributes to 
the economic development and well-being of the people. They 
also stressed the convenience of strengthening commercial 
relations in the hemisphere. They reject the implementation of 
unilateral measures that could affect international free trade 
and urge that the economic, commercial, and financial blockade 
of Cuba be lifted and manifest their support of the U.N. 
resolution on the issue. This is the first time since its 
creation in 1975 that SELA adopts an energetic attitude against 
the United States' hostile policy toward Cuba. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

