<F P=100> CENTRAL AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> El Salvador </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Offered Troops for Peacekeeping Force </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Offered Troops for Peacekeeping Force </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0306210194 San Salvador EL DIARIO DE HOY in Spanish 3 Jun 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0306210194 </F>
<F P=104>  San Salvador EL DIARIO DE HOY </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Salvadoran Government has offered the United 
Nations part of its Army for a future peacekeeping force, 
President Armando Calderon Sol has said. 
  The Salvadoran president has said "El Salvador is unable to 
receive Haitian refugees," but he said "what he can offer the 
world is a professional, technical, and ethical armed force that 
can be ready for any UN mission if it needs brave men for a 
peacekeeping force." 
  He has said "the United Nations knows it has a very 
professional armed force in El Salvador," adding the Salvadoran 
Government has already expressed the Army's willingness to 
assist. 
  The government did not reveal the number of troops offered 
to 
the United Nations, but he said El Salvador has helicopter 
pilots with advanced training and other military specialists who 
can contribute to the international community. 
  He has reiterated the United Nations can make the request, 
"which would be considered with great appreciation, because the 
Salvadoran Army is a professional and very technical Army." 
  Moreover, Honduran President Carlos Roberto Reina has 
rejected an eventual U.S. invasion of Haiti. "We reject 
invasions of any country," he has said. 

</TEXT>

