<F P=100> Nicaragua </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chamorro on El Salvador Visit, Haitian Refugees </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chamorro on El Salvador Visit, Haitian Refugees </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0506000694 Managua Sistema Nacional de Television Network 
in Spanish 0200 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0506000694 </F>
<F P=104>  Managua Sistema Nacional de Television Network 
in Spanish 0200 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=105> Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Vilma Estrada; from the "National Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] President Violeta Chamorro, upon returning from El 
Salvador, reported that high-ranking U.S. Government officials 
cite Nicaragua as an example of democratic transition in the 
Central American region. She flew to San Salvador to attend the 
inauguration of President Armando Calderon Sol. President 
Violeta Chamorro said she met with Strobe Talbott, U.S. under 
secretary of state, and Alexander Watson, assistant secretary of 
state for inter-American affairs. The U.S. officials requested 
her support for the U.S. initiatives at the United Nations and 
OAS directed at restoring democracy in Haiti, because Nicaragua 
is an example of democracy. This opinion is shared by the other 
officials with whom she met during her visit. 
  [Begin Chamorro recording] Everyone looks positively at 
Nicaragua and its people. I held interviews with 
representatives of the United States, China, Spain, and many 
other countries. All of them said: Dona Violeta, we 
congratulate you for your good administration. I have heard 
many expressions of support and received many ovations, which I 
sincerely believe are for the Nicaraguan people. [end recording] 
  When asked about the U.S. request for support in receiving 
Haitian refugees, she said that her colleagues in the region are 
studying the situation and will respond during the December 
Summit of the Americas in Miami. 
  [Begin Chamorro recording] I believe that working together 
or alone to find well-being for Haiti is worthwhile. I remember 
perfectly well when members of the Farabundo Marti National 
Liberation Front came and asked me: What can we do, Dona 
Violeta, to start talks in El Salvador and find peace there? I 
told them that the best way was to try, and now they have peace. 
That is what they told me. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

