<F P=100> Nicaragua </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gurdian Considers Presidential Candidacy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Gurdian Considers Presidential Candidacy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   94P20835A </F>
<F P=103> 94P20835A </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
CSO 

    [Editorial Report] Managua LA TRIBUNA in Spanish of 10 May 
1994 on page 3A reports that Higher Council of Private 
Enterprise (Cosep) President Ramiro Gurdian would be "willing" 
to be the National Conservative Party's candidate for president 
of Nicaragua in 1996. In his appearance on Channel 2's "Buenos 
Dias" program, Gurdian criticized the executive branch for being 
slow to resolve the property issue. In contrast, he cited 
examples of cases being resolved quickly under U.S. pressure. 
Gurdian related the accusations he had heard from peasants that 
military personnel are carrying out attacks in the north. With 
regard to the Sandinist National Liberation Front (FSLN), he 
explained that Cosep is interested in a dialogue with the FSLN 
"in order to seek concrete solutions for Nicaragua," but that 
this should "in no way be interpreted as seeking an alliance 
with Sandinism." 

</TEXT>

