<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Endara Would Not Back, Condemn Haiti Invasion </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Endara Would Not Back, Condemn Haiti Invasion </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0506173194 Panama City LA PRENSA in Spanish 5 Jun 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PA0506173194 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City LA PRENSA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Jose Quintero] </F>
  [Text] President Guillermo Endara Galimany said that if the 
United States decides to invade Haiti to remove General Raoul 
Cedras and his men from power, he will not support it, but if it 
takes place he would not condemn it either. 
  Questioned by numerous journalists at the Yellow Room of the 
Presidential Palace after signing the Chapultepec Declaration, 
Endara said he believes the invasion of Panama in December 1989 
did not take place because of a right or a duty. 
  "We did not ask for the invasion... it took place... 
historic 
situations, which will be up to analysts to study." 
  According to the Panamanian president, between Haiti and 
Panama, there are distant but similar conditions, which he 
discussed with U.S. Vice President Al Gore during a recent 
dinner in Tegucigalpa. 
  He noted that on that occasion Gore said Haitian President 
Jean Bertrand Aristide won his country's elections with 70 
percent of the votes, a similar percentage with which he 
(Endara) won the 1989 elections from his opponent, Carlos Duque 
from the National Liberation Coalition. 
  "I am not calling for an invasion of Haiti, but I do not 
exclude it either," the president said. When asked again if he 
would support an invasion, he said no, but that if the United 
States invades the island, he will not condemn it. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

