<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Endara Backs Court on Electoral Tribunal Reform </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Endara Backs Court on Electoral Tribunal Reform </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0506164794 Panama City LA PRENSA in Spanish 3 Jun 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PA0506164794 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City LA PRENSA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Ibeth Vega G.] </F>
  [Excerpts] President Guillermo Endara yesterday expressed 
his agreement with the Supreme Court's opposition to the 
constitutional reforms that grant the Electoral Tribunal the 
power to interpret the Constitution on electoral issues. 
  Endara indicated that if the Electoral Tribunal members "do 
not make the corrections quickly, I believe the bill (with the 
constitutional reforms) is in danger of failing." 
  Endara's remarks come after the Supreme Court announced its 
opposition to the constitutional reforms that permit the 
Electoral Tribunal to interpret the Constitution on electoral 
issues. The Supreme Court considers the reforms "inadvisable" 
for the administration of justice. 
  "I know the court's opinion, and I personally agree with 
it," 
added Endara. [passage omitted] 
  The executive branch presented to the Legislative Assembly 
two constitutional reforms to grant autonomy to the Electoral 
Tribunal and to eliminate the possibility of an army existing in 
the country. 
  Nevertheless, according to Supreme Court President Arturo 
Hoyos, the justices unanimously agree that the first reform is 
inadvisable. 
  "In the way it has been proposed, this reform might be a 
source of constant conflict between the Electoral Tribunal and 
the Supreme Court of Justice," Hoyos added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

