<F P=100> Bolivia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Indigenous Groups Hold Preparatory Meeting in Cochabamba </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Indigenous Groups Hold Preparatory Meeting in Cochabamba </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0306133494 Madrid EFE in Spanish 2237 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY0306133494 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cochabamba, Bolivia 1 Jun (EFE) -- The preparatory 
meeting for the "International Decade of the World's Indigeous 
People" closed today in Cochabamba, Bolivia, with the approval 
of a document to be submitted to the United Nations. 
  The document contains 53 resolutions vindicating the 
cultural 
identity of indigenous peoples, along with their political, 
social and economic rights. 
  Guatemalan Nobel Peace Laureate Rigoberta Menchu presided 
over the meeting which started on 31 May. She stated today that 
indigenous peoples hope their demands will be formally 
recognized by all UN member-countries. 
  Menchu said the resolutions approved in Cochabamba will 
become mandatory for all countries worldwide once they are 
approved by the UN General Assembly. 
  Commenting on what transpired during the meeting in 
Cochabamba, some 400 km east of La Paz, Bolivian Vice President 
Victor Hugo Cardenas -- himself an Aymara Indian -- said: 
"Indigenous peoples can achieve development without renouncing 
their own culture." 
  The "International Decade of the World's Indigenous People" 
starts on 10 December 1994 and closes on 9 December 2004. 
  Beside Menchu and Cardenas, 120 delegates from diverse 
indigenous communities and government organizations from 
different countries attended the meeting in Cochabamba. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

