<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Cautious Stance' Adopted on Armed Intervention in Haiti </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Cautious Stance' Adopted on Armed Intervention in Haiti </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0406004694 Brasilia Voz do Brasil Network in Portuguese 
2200 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY0406004694 </F>
<F P=104>  Brasilia Voz do Brasil Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Brazilian Government has adopted a cautious 
stance concerning the news that the ousted president of Haiti, 
Jean-Bertrand Aristide, has apparently endorsed armed 
intervention in his country. 
  This would be Aristide's solution for reinstatement as 
president, from which post he was unseated in 1991 by a military 
junta. The news was released today by an international news 
agency. Foreign Minister Celso Amorim stated that the Brazilian 
Government feels that the use of force would be an extreme 
measure. Amorim believes this is a complex question, and one 
first has to see whether the sanctions applied by the United 
Nations against the Haitian military yield positive results. He 
said: 
  [Begin Amorim recording] For the time being, the United 
Nations, the UN Security Council -- the appropriate body to 
apply coercive measures -- has renewed and stepped up sanctions 
against the de facto Haitian Government. I think we have to 
verify whether these more stringent sanctions are working. 
Moreover, an armed intervention is a most complex question. It 
is difficult... [pauses] We acknowledge the legitimate objective 
of having President Aristide reinstated in office, and we have 
supported this, but the use of force is something that always 
inspires caution and needs to be examined with great care. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

